Sir '''Douglas Clague''' [[CBE]], [[Military Cross|MC]], [[Queen's Police Medal|QPM]], [[Colonial Police Medal|CPM]], [[Territorial Decoration|TD]] (13 June 1917 – 11 March 1981) was a British Hong Kong soldier and entrepreneur who spent most of his life in [[Hong Kong]].<ref>https://gwulo.com/node/6195</ref>

==Early Years==
Born in [[South Rhodesia]], in 1917<ref>http://www.ejinsight.com/20171215-Hong-Kongs-ties-with-Zimbabwe-past-and-the-present/</ref>, Clague arrived in [[Hong Kong]] in 1940 as a [[lieutenant]] in the [[Royal Artillery]], and on the outbreak of [[World War II]] became a prisoner in the [[Sham Shui Po]] [[PoW]] camp.<ref name=trouble>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,946594,00.html HONG KONG: Trouble in the Hongs], [[Time magazine]], 20 October 1975</ref> He later escaped, and joined the [[British Army Aid Group]] in [[Free China (Second Sino-Japanese War)|free China]].<ref>https://gwulo.com/node/6195</ref> On the ending of the war, he famously took the surrender of [[Japan]]ese forces in [[Bangkok]] more or less single-handedly.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestandard.com.hk/news_print.asp?art_id=735&sid=4378537 |title=China's Business Newspaper |publisher=The Standard |date= |accessdate=2013-09-20}}</ref>

==Business Career and Involvements in Hong Kong==
After the war, he became the [[tai-pan]] of with the British Hong Kong [[hong (business)|hong]] [[Hutchison Whampoa|Hutchison]], better known as Hutchison Whampoa. 

He overstretched his finances, which resulted in [[HSBC]] taking over the firm, replacing Clague, and lead to the sale of Hutchison Whampoa to [[Li Ka-Shing|Li Ka-Shing's]] [[Cheung Kong]] in 1979.<ref name=otherhandover>Stephen Vines, [http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1090780,00.html?iid=chix-sphere The Other Handover], [[Time magazine]], 6 August 2005</ref>

Clague was also one of the commandants of the [[Royal Hong Kong Auxiliary Police Force]], and a member of both the [[Executive Council of Hong Kong|Executive]] and the [[Legislative Council (Hong Kong)|Legislative Council]]s of Hong Kong, when he succeeded [[Cedric Blaker]] on 21 March 1958. From 1950 to 1951 he was President of the Gunners Roll of Hong Kong.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gunnersroll.org/documents |title=Documents |publisher=Gunners Roll |date= |accessdate=2013-09-20}}</ref>

Clague owned a [[wikt:lodge|lodge]] at [[Kam Tsin]] in the northern [[New Territories]] alongside many other wealthy people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ebook.lib.hku.hk/HKG/B35833361.pdf |title=Royal Hong Kong Auxiliary Police Force : Silver Jubilee 1959-1984 |publisher=Ebook.lib.hku.hk |accessdate=2013-09-20}}</ref> He was also a [[racehorse]] owner and one time chairman of the [[Royal Hong Kong Jockey Club]]; it was under his tenure the [[Sha Tin Racecourse]] was developed. The [[Clague Garden Estate]] in [[Tsuen Wan]] is named for him<ref>https://www.hkhs.com/en/housing_archive/id/10/scheme/4</ref>, as he was also one of the longest serving chairmen of the [[Hong Kong Housing Society]].

==Personal==

Clague was married to Lady Margaret Isolin Clague (née Cowley) and three children (Jonathan, Penny and Isolin).<ref>http://notices.irishtimes.com/death/clague-lady-margaret/8235829</ref>

He died of cancer aged 64, in 1981<ref>https://gwulo.com/node/14667</ref> and Lady Clague in 2011.

