{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}} {{Infobox person | name = Gianni Mattioli | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 1903 | birth_place = Milan, Italy | death_date = 1977 | death_place = Milan, Italy | death_cause = | restingplace = | nationality = Italian | residence = Milan, Italy | education = | alma mater = | occupation = cotton trader | title = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | known for = art collection | boards = | salary = | networth = | spouse = | children = [[Laura Mattioli Rossi]] | parents = | relations = | website = }}
[[File:Umberto Boccioni, 1913, Dynamism of a Cyclist (Dinamismo di un ciclista), oil on canvas, 70 x 95 cm, Gianni Mattioli Collection, on long-term loan to the Peggy Guggenheim Collection, Venice.jpg|thumb|''Dynamism of a Cyclist'', [[Umberto Boccioni]], 1913. Gianni Mattioli Collection, on long-term loan to the Peggy Guggenheim Collection, Venice.]] '''Gianni Mattioli''' (1903 – 1977) was an Italian businessman, a cotton trader in Milan, and art collector, particularly of the work of the Italian [[Futurist]]s.
Mattioli was born in [[Milan]] in 1903, and started collecting in the early 1920s, but most of his collection was built in the late 1930s and 1940s, and in 1949, he acquired 87 works from fellow Italian collector [[Pietro Feroldi]] (1881–1958).<ref name="metmuseum1">{{cite web|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/art/libraries-and-research-centers/leonard-lauder-research-center/programs-and-resources/index-of-cubist-art-collectors/mattioli|title=Mattioli, Gianni : Milan, 1903–Milan, 1977|website=Metmuseum.org|accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref>
Mattioli died in Milan in 1977, and his daughter the art historian, [[Laura Mattioli Rossi]], inherited the collection.<ref name="metmuseum1"/>
26 works from the Gianni Mattioli Collection have been on loan to the [[Peggy Guggenheim Collection]] in Venice since September 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guggenheim-venice.it/inglese/collections/collection2.php?id_cat=14 |title=Guggenheim |website=Guggenheim-venice.it |date= |accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref>
In November 2015, ''[[Nu couché]]'' a 1917 [[Amedeo Modigliani]] oil on canvas from the collection, was sold by his daughter at Christie's, New York for $170.4 million to [[Liu Yiqian]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Everett |first=Christopher |url=https://www.tharawat-magazine.com/facts/most-expensive-art-sales-in-history/ |title=10 Most Expensive Art Sales in History |publisher=Tharawat Magazine |date= |accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref>
